What the telemetry shows (evidence):
- Multiple carts service KPIs breached their global P95 in the window: cpu, mem, socket, latency-50, latency-90, and workload. Earliest workload/latency exceedance for carts appears at ~2024-01-18T20:53:00Z; additional peaks around 21:11–21:13Z (cpu/socket/latency/mem). These are consecutive points (not single noise spikes) and multiple resource KPIs are affected.
- Supporting components (carts-db) show disk I/O and memory anomalies later in the window (~21:13Z), consistent with downstream resource pressure after carts was impacted.
- Log telemetry shows traffic/row_count spikes at front-end, orders, and user starting around 2024-01-18T20:53:00Z (each had points above their global P95). log.error_count and error_logs contain no error spikes or error messages in the window.

Reasoning to localize root cause:
- Metrics identify actual resource faults first; carts is the top metric-level candidate because it had the most distinct KPI series breaching P95 (cpu, mem, socket, latency, workload).
- Traces are unavailable, so we use logs to understand traffic flow. Logs indicate an upstream traffic spike (front-end → orders → user) beginning ~20:53:00Z, which temporally aligns with the earliest carts workload/latency anomalies at ~20:53:00Z.
- No application error logs were observed, suggesting this is not an application exception but resource saturation due to load.
- The later appearance of carts-db diskio/mem anomalies (~21:13Z) fits propagation: carts overloaded first, then increased load on carts-db.

Conclusion supported by evidence: carts shows multi-resource degradation concurrent with an upstream traffic spike; the pattern is consistent with resource exhaustion rather than network packet loss or socket exceptions recorded in logs. The strongest and earliest metric signal for a resource being stressed is CPU/workload on carts (plus socket and memory symptoms).
